    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-03-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-03-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="371"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d371">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Bigelow</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 58.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-03-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 6, 1865.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your despatch of the 10th instant, No. 27,
                    relative to the effects produced by the reading of the encyclical letter of the
                    Pope by certain bishops of France to their congregations, in defiance of the
                    warning issued by the imperial government, has been received. I consider it a
                    very interesting paper upon an important question in the domestic politics of
                    France.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John Bigelow,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,
                            &amp;c., &amp;c</hi>.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
